\begin_layout Subsection
Manipulating the logger data
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Flex CharStyle:pkg
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
svUnit
\end_layout

\end_inset

 provides a series of methods and tools to manipulate the log file from
 the command line, in particular, 
\begin_inset Flex CharStyle:code
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
stats()
\end_layout

\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Flex CharStyle:code
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
summary()
\end_layout

\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Flex CharStyle:code
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
metadata()
\end_layout

\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Flex CharStyle:code
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
ls()
\end_layout

\end_inset

:
\end_layout

\begin_layout R-Chunk
<<>>=
\end_layout

\begin_layout R-Chunk
# Clear test exclusion list (to run test suites defined in svUnit)
\end_layout

\begin_layout R-Chunk
options(svUnit.excludeList = NULL)
\end_layout

\begin_layout R-Chunk
# Clear the log
\end_layout

\begin_layout R-Chunk
clearLog()
\end_layout

\begin_layout R-Chunk
# Run all currently defined tests, including test suites in svUnit
\end_layout

\begin_layout R-Chunk
runTest(svSuiteList(), name = "AllTests")
\end_layout

\begin_layout R-Chunk
# Get some statistics
\end_layout

\begin_layout R-Chunk
stats(Log())[, 1:3]
\end_layout

\begin_layout R-Chunk
# A slightly different presentation than print
\end_layout

\begin_layout R-Chunk
summary(Log())
\end_layout

\begin_layout R-Chunk
# Metadata collected on the machine where tests are run
\end_layout

\begin_layout R-Chunk
metadata(Log())
\end_layout

\begin_layout R-Chunk
# List content of the log
\end_layout

\begin_layout R-Chunk
ls(Log())
\end_layout

\begin_layout R-Chunk
@
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
As you can see, 
\begin_inset Flex CharStyle:code
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
ls()
\end_layout

\end_inset

 lists all components recorded in the test suite.
 Each component is a 
\begin_inset Flex CharStyle:var
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
svTestData
\end_layout

\end_inset

 object inheriting from 
\begin_inset Flex CharStyle:var
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
data.frame
\end_layout

\end_inset

, and it can be easily accessed through the 
\begin_inset Flex CharStyle:code
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
$
\end_layout

\end_inset

 operator.
 There are, of course similar methods defined for those 
\begin_inset Flex CharStyle:var
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
svTestData
\end_layout

\end_inset

 objects, like 
\begin_inset Flex CharStyle:code
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
print()
\end_layout

\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Flex CharStyle:code
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
summary()
\end_layout

\end_inset

, and 
\begin_inset Flex CharStyle:code
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
stats()
\end_layout

\end_inset

:
\end_layout

\begin_layout R-Chunk
<<>>=
\end_layout

\begin_layout R-Chunk
myTest <- Log()$testCube
\end_layout

\begin_layout R-Chunk
class(myTest)
\end_layout

\begin_layout R-Chunk
myTest
\end_layout

\begin_layout R-Chunk
summary(myTest)
\end_layout

\begin_layout R-Chunk
stats(myTest)
\end_layout

\begin_layout R-Chunk
@
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
As the logger inherits from 
\begin_inset Flex CharStyle:var
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
environment
\end_layout

\end_inset

, you can manage individual test data the same way as objects in any other
 environment.
 For instance, if you want to delete a particular test data without touching
 to the rest, you can use:
\end_layout

\begin_layout R-Chunk
<<>>=
\end_layout

\begin_layout R-Chunk
ls(Log())
\end_layout

\begin_layout R-Chunk
rm(test_R, envir = Log())
\end_layout

\begin_layout R-Chunk
ls(Log())
\end_layout

\begin_layout R-Chunk
@
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
As we will see in the following section, 
\begin_inset Flex CharStyle:pkg
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
svUnit
\end_layout

\end_inset

 proposes several means to organize individual assertions in various modules
 within a logical organization: 
\series bold
test functions
\series default
, 
\series bold
test units
\series default
 and 
\series bold
test suites
\series default
.
 This organization is inspired from 
\begin_inset Flex CharStyle:pkg
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
RUnit
\end_layout

\end_inset

, but with additional ways of using tests in interactive sessions (for instance,
 the ability to attach a test to the objects to be tested).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Test function
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The first organization level for grouping assertions together is the 
\series bold
test function
\series default
.
 A test function is a function without arguments whose name must start with
 
\begin_inset Flex CharStyle:var
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
test
\end_layout

\end_inset

.
 It typically contains a series of assertions applied to one object, method,
 or function to be checked (this is not obligatory, assertions are not restricte
d to one object, but good practices strongly suggest it).
 Here is an example:
\end_layout

\begin_layout R-Chunk
<<>>=
\end_layout

\begin_layout R-Chunk
test_function <- function() {
\end_layout

\begin_layout R-Chunk
    checkTrue(1 < 2, "check1")
\end_layout

\begin_layout R-Chunk
    v <- 1:3  # The reference
\end_layout

\begin_layout R-Chunk
    w <- 1:3  # The value to compare to the reference
\end_layout

\begin_layout R-Chunk
    checkEquals(v, w)
\end_layout

\begin_layout R-Chunk
}
\end_layout

\begin_layout R-Chunk
test_function <- as.svTest(test_function)
\end_layout

\begin_layout R-Chunk
is.svTest(test_function)
\end_layout

\begin_layout R-Chunk
@
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A test function should be made a special object called 
\begin_inset Flex CharStyle:var
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
svTest
\end_layout

\end_inset

, so that 
\begin_inset Flex CharStyle:pkg
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
svUnit
\end_layout

\end_inset

 can recognize it.
 This 
\begin_inset Flex CharStyle:var
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
svTest
\end_layout

\end_inset

 object, is allowed to live alone (for instance, loaded in 
\begin_inset Flex CharStyle:code
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
.GlobalEnv
\end_layout

\end_inset

, defined in a 
\begin_inset Flex CharStyle:proglang
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
R
\end_layout

\end_inset

 script, etc...
 in 
\begin_inset Flex CharStyle:pkg
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
svUnit
\end_layout

\end_inset

, while in 
\begin_inset Flex CharStyle:pkg
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
RUnit
\end_layout

\end_inset

, it must be located in a unit test).
 In 
\begin_inset Flex CharStyle:pkg
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
svUnit
\end_layout

\end_inset

 (not 
\begin_inset Flex CharStyle:pkg
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
RUnit
\end_layout

\end_inset

), you run this test simply by using 
\begin_inset Flex CharStyle:code
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
runTest()
\end_layout

\end_inset

, which returns the results invisibly (and you are supposed to access results
 from the logger):
\end_layout

\begin_layout R-Chunk
<<>>=
\end_layout

\begin_layout R-Chunk
clearLog()
\end_layout

\begin_layout R-Chunk
runTest(test_function)
\end_layout

\begin_layout R-Chunk
Log()
\end_layout

\begin_layout R-Chunk
@
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Now, a test function is most likely designed to test an 
\begin_inset Flex CharStyle:proglang
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
R
\end_layout

\end_inset

 object.
 
\begin_inset Flex CharStyle:pkg
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
svUnit
\end_layout

\end_inset

 also provides facilities to attach the test function to the object to be
 tested.
 Hence, the test cases and the tested object conveniently form a single
 entity that one can manipulate, copy, save, reload, etc.
 with all the usual tools in 
\begin_inset Flex CharStyle:proglang
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
R
\end_layout

\end_inset

.
 This association is simply made using 
\begin_inset Flex CharStyle:code
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
test(myobj) <-
\end_layout

\end_inset

:
\end_layout

\begin_layout R-Chunk
<<>>=
\end_layout

\begin_layout R-Chunk
# A very simple function
\end_layout

\begin_layout R-Chunk
Square <- function(x) return(x^2)
\end_layout

\begin_layout R-Chunk

\end_layout

\begin_layout R-Chunk
# A test case to associate with the Square() function
\end_layout

\begin_layout R-Chunk
test(Square) <- function() {
\end_layout

\begin_layout R-Chunk
    checkEquals(9, Square(3))
\end_layout

\begin_layout R-Chunk
    checkEquals(c(1, 4, 9), Square(1:3))
\end_layout

\begin_layout R-Chunk
    checkException(Square("xx"))
\end_layout

\begin_layout R-Chunk
}
\end_layout

\begin_layout R-Chunk
is.test(Square) # Does this object contain tests?
\end_layout

\begin_layout R-Chunk
@
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
One can retrieve the test associated with the object by using:
\end_layout

\begin_layout R-Chunk
<<>>=
\end_layout

\begin_layout R-Chunk
test(Square)
\end_layout

\begin_layout R-Chunk
@
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
And of course, running the test associated with an object is as easy as:
\end_layout

\begin_layout R-Chunk
<<>>=
\end_layout

\begin_layout R-Chunk
runTest(Square)
\end_layout

\begin_layout R-Chunk
Log()  # Remember we didn't clear log, so we add to the report here
\end_layout

\begin_layout R-Chunk
@
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Now that you master test functions, you should discover how you can group
 them in logical 
\series bold
units
\series default
, and associate them to 
\begin_inset Flex CharStyle:proglang
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
R
\end_layout

\end_inset

 packages.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Test units
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A 
\series bold
unit
\series default
 is a coherent piece of software that can be tested separately from the
 rest.
 Typically, a 
\begin_inset Flex CharStyle:proglang
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
R
\end_layout

\end_inset

 package is a structured way to compile and distribute such code units in
 
\begin_inset Flex CharStyle:proglang
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
R
\end_layout

\end_inset

.
 Hence, we need a mean to organize tests related to this unit conveniently.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Since a package can contain several functions, data frames, or other objects,
 our unit should collect together individual test functions related to each
 of these objects composing our package.
 Also, the test unit should accommodate the well-define organization of
 a package, and should integrate also in the already existing testing features
 of 
\begin_inset Flex CharStyle:proglang
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
R
\end_layout

\end_inset

, in particular with 
\begin_inset Flex CharStyle:command
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

R CMD check
\end_layout

\end_inset

.
 In both 
\begin_inset Flex CharStyle:pkg
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
RUnit
\end_layout

\end_inset

, and 
\begin_inset Flex CharStyle:pkg
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
svUnit
\end_layout

\end_inset

, one can define such test units, and they are made code compatible between
 them (at least for version 0.4-17 of 
\begin_inset Flex CharStyle:pkg
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
